{{Infobox Ancient Aristocrat | Name = Kagawake | image = | image_Size = | image_Caption = | Era = [[Kofun period]] | Birth_Date = Unknown | Death_Date = Unknown | Alternate_Names = Kagawake no Mikoto, Kannagiwake, Kannagiwake no Mikoto, Kagawake no Ō, Kagawake no Mikoto | Posthumous_Name = | Deity_Name = | Dharma_Name = | Burial_Place = | Titles = [[Ukita no Kuni no Miyatsuko|First Ukita Kuni no Miyatsuko]] | Allegiances = [[Emperor Seimu]], [[Empress Jingū]], [[Emperor Ōjin]] | Clan = {{ill|Kamitsuke Clan|ja|上毛野氏|1=Kamitsukeno clan|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamitsuke Clan|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamitsukeno clan|qq=}}, {{ill|Shimosuke Clan|ja|下毛野氏|1=Shimotsukeno clan|lt=Shimotsukeno clan|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shimosuke Clan|13=User:Immanuelle/Shimotsukeno clan|qq=}}, Ancestor of the {{ill|Kibiya clan|ja|吉弥侯部|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kibiya Clan|qq=}} | Parents = | Spouse = | Children = | Notable_Features = }} '''Kagawake''' (かがわけ{{Sfn|Kagawake (Ancient Clan)|2010}}, birth and death dates unknown) is a historical figure from the {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kofun period|qq=}} referenced in the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Shoki|qq=}} and other historical texts. He was the first '''{{ill|Ukita no Kuni no Miyatsuko|ja|浮田国造|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ukita no Kuni no Miyatsuko|qq=}}''', an ancestor of the {{ill|Kamitsuke Clan|ja|上毛野氏|1=Kamitsukeno clan|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamitsuke Clan|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamitsukeno clan|qq=}} and {{ill|Kibiya clan|ja|吉弥侯部|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kibiya Clan|qq=}}. Kagawake is described as a general sent to the Korean Peninsula under {{ill|Empress Jingū|ja|神功皇后|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Empress Jingū|qq=}}'s reign. The "Kannagiwake" (巫別) mentioned during the {{ill|Emperor Ōjin|ja|応神天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Ōjin|qq=}} period is believed to be the same individual{{Sfn|Kagawake (Ancient Clan)|2010}}.
== Records ==
The {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Shoki|qq=}} records Kagawake's involvement in the following events: * In the 49th year of {{ill|Empress Jingū|ja|神功皇后|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Empress Jingū|qq=}}, he was appointed a general alongside {{ill|Aratawake|ja|荒田別|1=Aratawake|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Aratawake|13=User:Immanuelle/Aratawake|qq=}} to subjugate {{ill|Silla|ja|新羅|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Silla|qq=}}. His return to Japan is noted in the 50th year. * In the 15th year of {{ill|Emperor Ōjin|ja|応神天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Ōjin|qq=}}, "Kannagiwake" was dispatched with Aratawake to {{ill|Baekje|ja|百済|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Baekje|qq=}}. The following year, they returned with {{ill|Wani|ja|王仁|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wani|qq=}}. "Kannagiwake" is identified with Kagawake{{Sfn|Kagawake (Ancient Clan)|2010}}. This record also describes Aratawake and Kannagiwake as "ancestors of the Kamitsuke Clan." * According to the {{ill|Sendai Kuji Hongi|ja|先代旧事本紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sendai Kuji Hongi|qq=}}, "Kuni no Miyatsuko Hongi" section, "Kagawake no Ō," a fifth-generation descendant of {{ill|Emperor Sujin|ja|崇神天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Sujin|qq=}}, was appointed as the Ukita no Kuni no Miyatsuko under {{ill|Emperor Seimu|ja|成務天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Seimu|qq=}}'s reign.
The name Kagawake also appears in the {{ill|Sumiyoshi Taisha Jindaiki|ja|住吉大社神代記|1=Sumiyoshi Taisha Shrine Chronicles|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sumiyoshi Taisha Jindaiki|13=User:Immanuelle/Sumiyoshi Taisha Shrine Chronicles|qq=}} in the context of the Silla expedition.
== Analysis ==
Kagawake's existence is debated among scholars. Some argue he was a historical figure based on the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Shoki|qq=}}, genealogical records, and references in the {{ill|Baekje Annals|ja|百済記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Baekje Annals|qq=}}. Others suggest he is a later legendary addition{{Sfn|Kagawake (Ancient Clan)|2010}}.
The phonetic similarity of "Kaga" has led to theories linking Kagawake to {{ill|Ashikaga District|ja|足利郡|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ashikaga District|qq=}}, present-day {{ill|Ashikaga|ja|足利市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ashikaga|qq=}}, Tochigi Prefecture. Some traditions suggest Kagawake is connected to the origin of the place name "Ashikaga." <ref>{{Cite book|title=Japanese Geographic Resources|chapter=Research on Keno Province in the Kofun Period}}</ref>
