The [[:en:Nihon Shoki|Nihon Shoki]] records Kagawake's involvement in the following events: * In the 49th year of [[:en:Empress Jingū|Empress Jingū]], he was appointed a general alongside {{ill|Aratawake|ja|荒田別|1=Aratawake|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Aratawake|13=User:Immanuelle/Aratawake|qq=}} to subjugate [[:en:Silla|Silla]]. His return to Japan is noted in the 50th year. * In the 15th year of [[:en:Emperor Ōjin|Emperor Ōjin]], "Kannagiwake" was dispatched with Aratawake to [[:en:Baekje|Baekje]]. The following year, they returned with [[:en:Wani (scholar)|Wani]]. "Kannagiwake" is identified with Kagawake{{Sfn|Kagawake (Ancient Clan)|2010}}. This record also describes Aratawake and Kannagiwake as "ancestors of the Kamitsuke Clan." * According to the [[:en:Kujiki|Sendai Kuji Hongi]], "Kuni no Miyatsuko Hongi" section, "Kagawake no Ō," a fifth-generation descendant of [[:en:Emperor Sujin|Emperor Sujin]], was appointed as the Ukita no Kuni no Miyatsuko under [[:en:Emperor Seimu|Emperor Seimu]]'s reign.
The name Kagawake also appears in the {{ill|Sumiyoshi Taisha Jindaiki|ja|住吉大社神代記|1=Sumiyoshi Taisha Shrine Chronicles|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sumiyoshi Taisha Jindaiki|13=User:Immanuelle/Sumiyoshi Taisha Shrine Chronicles|qq=}} in the context of the Silla expedition.
== Analysis ==
Kagawake's existence is debated among scholars. Some argue he was a historical figure based on the [[:en:Nihon Shoki|Nihon Shoki]], genealogical records, and references in the {{ill|Baekje Annals|ja|百済記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Baekje Annals|qq=}}. Others suggest he is a later legendary addition{{Sfn|Kagawake (Ancient Clan)|2010}}.
The phonetic similarity of "Kaga" has led to theories linking Kagawake to [[:en:Ashikaga District, Tochigi|Ashikaga District]], present-day [[:en:Ashikaga, Tochigi|Ashikaga]], Tochigi Prefecture. Some traditions suggest Kagawake is connected to the origin of the place name "Ashikaga." <ref>{{Cite book|title=Japanese Geographic Resources|chapter=Research on Keno Province in the Kofun Period}}</ref>
